  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Sustainable Livelihoods for the Ultra Poor: Alta Verapaz, Guatemala</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Provide training and seed capital grants to invest in livelihood activities, and organize community-based savings and credit groups to facilitate continued access to financial resources.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The extreme poor, particularly women</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Trickle Up aims to build sustainable livelihoods for extremely poor women through a combination of: training and coaching to help participants plan, expand and diversify their livelihood activities; asset transfers to support new livelihood activities; savings groups to provide a safety net and enable ongoing access to capital; and linkages to public services and preventative health messaging. The program is delivered through partnership with local organizations. Trickle Up participants are primarily from the Queqchi and Quich&#xC3;&#xA9; indigenous groups and live in remote rural communities, often an hour&#xE2;&#x20AC;&#x2122;s walk or a once a day bus ride to the nearest market. Between three and six months per year (known as the &apos;hungry season&apos;), many of our participants do not have enough to eat, and must migrate or borrow against next season&#xE2;&#x20AC;&#x2122;s harvest to survive. Without conventional employment options, self-employment is the only means of survival, which is why Trickle Up has a vital role to play.</narrative>
  </description>
